e, which will be followed\nby a flag raising ceremony. Keys to\nthe cabin will be given to Dr. Kilts\nat the ceremony and presentation\nUnemployment Benefits Available\nto IT orkers Jobless Because of\nW ork Stoppage: Labor Disputes\n\u201cApproximately 400.000 Michigan\nworkers have filed claims for unem\nployment benefits with the Michigan\nUnemployment Compensation Com\nmission since January 1, 1945\u201d, Eug\nene T. Dormer. Director, said today.\nThis means that over 22 r o o' all\nworkers covered by the Michigan\nUnemployment Compensation Law\nhave been unemployed at one time\nC\nI\nN\nZ\nE\nL\nS\nis\nA\nFINE\nPLACE\nTO\nBUY\nYOUR\n\u2014\"h\n204\nELM\nST.\nU\n2-diamond Bridal Set 1\nEach matched ring has a\nsparkling diamond. Both\ns99l\u00ae\nwill be made by an officer of the\nKiwanis.\nThe troop will then present a\nprogram for the parents, Kiwanis\nand guests. The ceremony will end\nwith the lowering of the flag, at\nwhich time. Russell Samis will\nshoot off a small canon.\nThe cabin on Grosse He was built\nfor Troop No. 8 by members of the\nWyandotte Kiwanis club. Dr. Ernest\nPox is chairman of the Kiwanis\nBoy Scout committee.\nor another since the first of the\nyear\u201d, he said.\nMichigan is now paying over $3,-\n000,000 each week in unemploy\nment benefit checks. At present,\nthere are 204.912 people whose claims\nare current. Michigan tops the na\ntion both in money paid out and\nthe number of people filing claims.\nThe following are the answers to\nthe questions most Jrequently asked\non unemployment compensaion.\n1. Q. What is unemployment com\npensation?\nA: It is insurance to pay rash\nbenefits to workers during periods\nbetween jobs and during lay-offs.\nIt is intended to provide some\nthing for them to live on while they\nare without work through no fault\nof their own. Unemployment com\npensation Is NOT charity; it comes\nto eligible workers as their right.\n2. Q: What if I am out of work be\ncause of a labor dispute? Will I be\ndisqualified for benefits?\nA: If you are unemployed because\nof a strike or a stoppage of work\nas the result of a labor dispute, your\neligibility for benefits depends on\nthe particular situation. For ex\nample. if a labor dispute in a plant\nof another employer causes your\ndepartment to close down, you may\nbe allowed your benefits. On the\nother hand, if you (or your class\nof employees) are detemined to be\n\u201cdirectly invoved in the dispute,\nbenefits may be denied you.\n3 Q: After I have registered for\nwork at the public employment of\nfice, and filed my claim for em\nployment compensation, must I ac\ncept any job that is offered me?\nA: To be entitled to benefits, you\nmust be willing to accept an offer\nof suitable work. A job's suitability\ndepends on such factors as your\npast work experience, the distance\nof the job from your home, the\nwages offered, and the local work\noportunities. The unemployment\ncompensation agency determines\neach case on its merits, but in no\ncase do you have to accept a job\nwhich offers wages or working con\nditions far less favorable than those\nprevailing in the locality for that\nkind of work.\n4 Q: What happens if I refuse a\njob?\nA: If the agency considers it\n\u201csuitable\", you will be disqualified,\nand your benefits will be reduced by\n3 to 5 weeks.\n5 Q:lf I am offered a job that is\nopen because of a labor dispute, and\nI refuse to accept it, will I be denied\nunemployment benefits?\nA: No, the law says that you may\nnot be disqualified for refusing to\naccept a job that is vacant due\ndirectly to a strike, lockout, or other\nlabor dispute.\nPledged To Fraternity\nGRENCASTLE. Ind., Oct. 11\n(Special)\u2014Paul D. Hodges, son of\nMr. and Mrs. Willis V. Hodges, 1256\nVinewood, has been pledged to Del\nta Tau Delta fraternity on the De-\nPauw University campus, according\nto an announcement made here.\nTen of DePauw\u2019s twelve national\nfraternities have announced their\nfirst pledge list with the opening\nof the winter semester on the\nGreencastle campus.\nThe possibilities of harnessing\natomic energy for use in the kitchen\nare being investigated.\nF\nU\nR\nN\nI\nT\nU\nR\nE\nCOMPLETE\nOPTICAL\nSERVICE\nDINNERWARE\nGLASSWARE\nSILVERWARE\nPOTTERY\nthe\nCHINA\nSHOP\nOAK at FIRST STREET\nA il II I\njll I ffl 1111 1 ill I\nBIG VALUES GOOD SELECTIONS FOR FIRST CHOICE, COME EARLY\n\nI |ir\u00abston*\nfactory-controlled I\nI RECAPPING\nOB NO OTHER RECAPPINO I\nOff jgK\u00dfm, GIVES YOU ALL THESEi I\nCamelback j\nAl Prompt, Cctiruous I\nOv Service 1\nOs WwHffld Workmanship\nVj Guaranteed\nVtiEBF Recapped with the I\n%QK 4p oTflf HFamous Firestone I\nFIRESTONE SUPER\nANTI-FREEZE\nQ in your own\n\u25a0I 9 contains\nBecause of a special soluble\noil seal, evaporation is\nreduced to a minimum.\nProtect your car by getting\nanti-freeze now.\nI Genuine Leather\nJIIImLFOLD\nI 1.45*\ng A handsome billfold you'll 1\nV be proud to use. Has plenty\nB of pockets for valuables.\nM.r Re 149 t\nl j 1 Heavy Duty\nImL BR\u00b0\u00b0M\nI 1.33\n1 Sweeps clean and\nfast! Fine quality\nbroom corn stur-\nIsm dily bound with i\nj H five rows of\nIPPPP stitching.\njX a\n\\X| HOUSE FUSES Stock up at this low price 4c ea. M\n5\u00ae PUTTY \u2014Won\u2019t shrink or crack 1 lb. 15c B\n'jfl m\nS\u00ae FORCE CUPS For clearing sinks and drains ,22c\n2\u00ae FIRST AID KlTS\u2014 Contain complete supplies 24c B\n\\I VARNISH REMOVER\u2014 Quick and easy. .14-pint 25c B\nKM TURPENTINE\u2014 Pure gum. Highest grade Qt. 45c B\n5\u00ae STEEL SKILLET\u2014 PopuIar nine-inch size 45c\nK\u00ae CURTAIN STRETCHER\u2014 No pins. Easy to use 66c B\nP\u00ae DRY CLEANER\u2014 Removes spots from any fabric. 77c B\nU PARCEL POST LAUNDRY CASE\u2014 Good quality 1.98 B\nA AA A Aj\u00df\nOPEN A CHARGE ACCOUNT OR, IF YOU PREFER,\nUSE OUR CONVENIENT BUDGET PLAN\nSET*\nBUY VICTORY BONDS\n1\nOIL FILTER\nCARTRIDGES i\nThey're Washablel J 1\nI\nANIMALS 77 H\\ I\nu\u00bb.. u{! IA!I\nChoice of several adorable B\nstyles. Safe for baby. B\n\n